<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a barcode?", answer: "A barcode is a machine-readable representation of data using a pattern of parallel lines (bars) of varying widths and spacings. The pattern encodes information such as product numbers, serial codes, or text strings that can be read by optical scanners or cameras. Barcodes were first patented in 1952 and became commercially successful in the 1970s with the introduction of the Universal Product Code (UPC) for retail inventory tracking. Today, barcodes are used in virtually every industry including retail, logistics, healthcare, manufacturing, and library management." },
  { question: "What is the difference between Code 128, EAN-13, and Code 39?", answer: "Code 128 is a high-density barcode that can encode all 128 ASCII characters (letters, digits, symbols, and control characters). It is widely used in shipping labels, packaging, and logistics. EAN-13 (European Article Number) is a 13-digit numeric-only barcode used internationally for retail product identification, equivalent to UPC-A with an extra digit. Code 39 (also called Code 3 of 9) is an older, lower-density format that supports uppercase letters, digits, and a few special characters. It is commonly used in government, military, and automotive industries." },
  { question: "How does Code 128 encoding work?", answer: "Code 128 uses three code sets (A, B, C) to encode different character ranges. Code Set B, which this generator uses, covers ASCII characters 32-127 (printable characters). Each character is encoded as a pattern of three bars and three spaces totaling 11 modules wide. The barcode includes a start character (identifying the code set), data characters, a modulo-103 checksum character computed from weighted values of all preceding characters, and a stop pattern. The checksum ensures data integrity when the barcode is scanned." },
  { question: "What is an EAN-13 check digit?", answer: "The 13th digit of an EAN-13 barcode is a check digit calculated from the first 12 digits using a weighted sum algorithm. Each odd-positioned digit (1st, 3rd, 5th, etc.) is multiplied by 1, and each even-positioned digit by 3. The products are summed, and the check digit is the value needed to bring the total to the next multiple of 10. For example, if the sum is 57, the check digit is 3 (because 60 - 57 = 3). This check digit allows scanners to verify that the barcode was read correctly and detect single-digit errors and most transposition errors." },
  { question: "Can I print barcodes generated by this tool?", answer: "Yes, the barcodes are generated as scalable SVG graphics that maintain crisp edges at any print resolution. Download the SVG for vector quality in print applications, or download the PNG at 3x resolution for raster use. For reliable scanning, ensure adequate quiet zones (white space) around the barcode, print at a minimum width of 25mm for Code 128 and EAN-13, use high contrast (black bars on white background), and avoid scaling below the minimum size. Test printed barcodes with a scanner before mass production to verify readability." }
]) %>

